  "text": "## Rust E0505 Error Origin Trace\n\nThe `error[E0505]: cannot move out of `x` because it is borrowed` error is generated through the following chain in the Rust compiler:\n\n### 1. MIR Borrow Checker Entry Point\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs`\n**Function**: `mir_borrowck` (line 117-138)\n\nThis is the main entry point for the borrow checker query. It initializes a `BorrowCheckRootCtxt` and calls `do_mir_borrowck()` to perform the borrow checking on the MIR (Mid-level IR).\n\n### 2. Borrow Conflict Detection\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs`\n**Function**: `check_access_for_conflict` (line 1246-1374)\n\nThis is the core function that detects move-while-borrowed violations. It:\n- Iterates through all borrows that might conflict with a memory access\n- When it finds a `WriteKind::Move` attempting to move a place that has an active borrow, it flags an error\n- Calls `report_move_out_while_borrowed` on line 1362 when this violation is detected\n\nThe key condition is on line 1361:\n```rust\nWriteKind::Move => {\n    this.report_move_out_while_borrowed(location, place_span, borrow)\n}\n```\n\n### 3. E0505 Error Generation\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/diagnostics/conflict_errors.rs`\n**Function**: `report_move_out_while_borrowed` (line 1533-1607)\n\nThis function generates the E0505 diagnostic when a move-while-borrowed violation is detected. It:\n- Retrieves borrow span information using `retrieve_borrow_spans`\n- Calls `cannot_move_when_borrowed` to create the diagnostic struct\n- Adds explanatory labels and suggestions using the borrow information\n\n### 4. Diagnostic Struct Definition\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/session_diagnostics.rs`\n**Struct**: `MoveBorrow` (line 284-295)\n\nThis is the derived diagnostic struct with the E0505 error code:\n```rust\n#[derive(Diagnostic)]\n#[diag(borrowck_cannot_move_when_borrowed, code = E0505)]\npub(crate) struct MoveBorrow<'a> {\n    pub place: &'a str,\n    pub borrow_place: &'a str,\n    pub value_place: &'a str,\n    #[primary_span]\n    #[label(borrowck_move_label)]\n    pub span: Span,\n    #[label]\n    pub borrow_span: Span,\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Error Helper Function\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrowck_errors.rs`\n**Function**: `cannot_move_when_borrowed` (line 16-31)\n\nThis helper function creates the `MoveBorrow` diagnostic struct and returns it as a `Diag<'infcx>`.\n\n### 6. Error Code Explanation\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_error_codes/src/error_codes/E0505.md`\n\nThis file provides the user-facing documentation explaining the E0505 error with examples and suggested fixes.\n\n### 7. Additional Move Error Diagnostics\n**File**: `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/diagnostics/move_errors.rs`\n\nThis file handles other illegal move scenarios including moves from borrowed content (`IllegalMoveOriginKind::BorrowedContent`), drops with active borrows, and moves from interior types.\n\n## Error Flow Summary\n\n1. `mir_borrowck` initiates borrow checking\n2. `check_access_for_conflict` detects when a `WriteKind::Move` tries to move a borrowed value\n3. `report_move_out_while_borrowed` is called to generate the error\n4. `cannot_move_when_borrowed` creates the `MoveBorrow` diagnostic struct\n5. The `MoveBorrow` struct with `code = E0505` formats and emits the error\n6. The error message includes the borrow span and move span with helpful context\n\nThe error message \"cannot move out of `x` because it is borrowed\" is generated by combining the place descriptions and the borrow information collected during the conflict detection phase."
